"Kill kill kill, there is a halfling coming for us to KILL!"<P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#212141><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/umalathorkerostasia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Malathor Kerostasia</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Registered User</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>2/13/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>4:56:10 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Practice Points, skills and armor?</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Dont worry much about practice points and skills, they pretty much are either unimportant or take care of themselves in EQ. If you are just about to start playing the one thing you should worry about is what class you are going to play. Class is everything in EQ, it determines what you will and what you will not be able to do. Figure out what style of player you are and find a class that matches that style of play. The rest will take care of itself.</font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#2F2F4F><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=bllackadder>Bllack Adder</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://24.221.41.117:8080/images/adder65.jpg BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Registered User</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>2/13/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>8:56:30 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><BR><img src=http://24.221.41.117:8080/images/adder65.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Practice Points, skills and armor?</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Welcome to EQ <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
You will find many people are helpfull and can teach you as you go. It is a big world and there is lots to explore!<br>
<br>
I agree with Malathor that the race/class combo you pick is most important. <br>
<br>
Trade skills are secondary in the game and in-combat skill gains are the usual way people increase their combat related skills for casting and fighting.<br>
<br>
Whatever you choose, follow these general principles:<br>
<br>
Priest classes (Druid, Shaman, Cleric) need wisdom first and foremost. Secondarily they need agility (for your armor class) So put 15 points to wis and 5 to agility.<br>
<br>
Int casters (Wiz, Mage, Necro, Chanter) need intelligence first. Secondarily put your extra 5 in agility. The exception to this is the Enchanter... they DO get mana from int, but also rely heavily on charisma for their particular spells. They are also the masters of fast mana regen, so many enchanters aim for a higher charisma than intelligence.<br>
<br>
Melee classes use the 4 first attributes most: Str, Agi, Dex, Sta. Rangers and Paladins use wisdom for mana. Shadowknights is int. Don't put extra points in wis/int for these though - you are primarily a meleer, the spells are a bonus which complete the character... they are not primary.<br>
<br>
Where to put the extra points out of those 4 for meleer's? Its hard to say... For monks and rogues IMHO max your Str. For Warr max your AGI.<br>
<br>
But the melee classes are much more debateable as to what is most important as opposed to the caster types. Just stick to the main 4 and you'll be ok.<br>
<br>
Next I strongly suggest you pick a good race. People will argue with me, but often they overlook being a complete newbie; its hard to remeber what it was like... Being a good race (no Ogre, Troll, Iksar, Darkelf) makes movement around the world much much easier and less dangerous.<br>
<br>
If you like to be a caster, which is sounds like... I warn you now that wizards are the most group dependent of the 4 int casters. In other words, while they can solo, they do it less efficiently and with greater risk to themselves than the other 3.<br>
<br>
The most solo friendly int caster is a necro, followed closely by the mage and chanter, with wizards a far 4th.<br>
<br>
Mages and Necros get 'pets'. These summonded obidient helpers are a major part of these classes. The enchanter can charm others to fight for them, but that can be unreliable... they also have pets, but these are weaker and less controllable than mages and necros.<br>
<br>
If you like to blow stuff up and solo be a mage. If you like to more subtly kill opponents over time and like to solo, be a necro. If you like to have the most complex class with the widest range of tricks, be a chanter. If you want to have THEE most powerful 1 shot 'nukes' be a wiz, they are the simplest, in that sense, of the int casters.<br>
<br>
Hope that helps.<br>
<br>
